SIMPLE: prince
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prince
<hw>Prince</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., from L.
<ets>princeps</ets>, <ets>-cipis</ets>, the first, chief;
<ets>primus</ets> first + <ets>capere</ets> to take. See <er>Prime</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>, and <er>Capacious</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The one
of highest rank; one holding the highest place and authority; a
sovereign; a monarch; -- originally applied to either sex, but now
rarely applied to a female.</def> <rj><au>Wyclif (Rev. i.
5).</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Go, Michael, of celestial armies <qex>prince</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Queen Elizabeth, a <qex>prince</qex> admirable above her sex.</q>
<rj><qau>Camden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The son of a king or emperor, or the issue of a
royal family; <as>as, <ex>princes</ex> of the blood</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A title belonging to persons of high rank, differing
in different countries. In England it belongs to dukes, marquises, and
earls, but is given to members of the royal family only. In Italy a
prince is inferior to a duke as a member of a particular order of
nobility; in Spain he is always one of the royal family.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The chief of any body of men; one at the head of a
class or profession; one who is pre⟦eum⟧minent; <as>as, a merchant
<ex>prince</ex>; a <ex>prince</ex> of players.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>prince</xex> of learning.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Peacham.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Prince-Albert coat</b></col>, <cd>a long double-breasted
frock coat for men.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Prince of the blood</b></col>,
<col><b>Prince consort</b></col>, <col><b>Prince of
darkness</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See under <er>Blood</er>,
<er>Consort</er>, and <er>Darkness</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Prince of
Wales</b></col>, <cd>the oldest son of the English sovereign.</cd> --
<col><b>Prince's feather</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a name given
to two annual herbs (<spn>Amarantus caudatus</spn> and <spn>Polygonum
orientale</spn>), with apetalous reddish flowers arranged in long
recurved panicled spikes.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Prince's
metal</b></col>, <col><b>Prince Rupert's metal</b></col></mcol>. See
under <er>Metal</er>. <col><b>Prince's pine</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld>
<cd>See <er>Pipsissewa</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prince</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Prince
<hw>Prince</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To play the prince.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Princedom</ent>⟦br⟧
